name: Jeri Mae
answer:
Swan neck is a term used to describe a deformity of the finger joints, specifically the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint. In this condition, the joint of the finger bends upward, resembling the shape of a swan's neck. 

Swan neck deformity is often associated with rheumatoid arthritis, but can also be caused by other conditions such as trauma, ligament injury, or congenital abnormalities. The abnormal bending of the finger joint can lead to difficulty in straightening the finger, causing problems with gripping and hand function. Treatment options for swan neck deformity may include splinting, physical therapy, medication, or in severe cases, surgical intervention.

name: Jeri Mae
answer: Swan neck is a condition or deformity that affects the fingers or toes, characterized by abnormal bending or hyperextension of the joint closest to the fingertip or toe. In this condition, the joint bends backward, resembling the curved neck of a swan. Swan neck deformity can be a result of various underlying conditions, such as rheumatoid arthritis, injury, or genetic predisposition. It can also occur due to imbalances in the muscles, ligaments, or tendons around the joint, resulting in the abnormal positioning. This deformity can cause functional issues and may require medical intervention or surgical correction, depending on the severity and associated symptoms.
